   286	## 6. Worlds, read routing, and the flag invariant (I17 repaired)
   287	
   288	### 6.1 Where worlds come from
   289	
   290	NEWEST outside passes; pass worlds from fork F2 (`mask ∪ lockedIn(root)`,
   291	pin, per-callstack `currentWorld` across yields — I6); committed-for-root
   292	for effect flushes and fixups; writer's world never materialized. A pass
   293	whose selection equals newest is RENDER_NEWEST: K0-routed reads, writes
   294	throw (guard keys on the pass binding, never world identity).
   295	
   296	### 6.2 Read routing (champion §5.2, unchanged)
   297	
   298	```
   299	read(node):                       // LOGGED build only; DIRECT read is donor-verbatim (§4)
   300	  w = currentWorld
   301	  if w is NEWEST or RENDER_NEWEST: return k0.pull(node)
   302	  if F(node) = 1:
   303	    if node is atom: return foldAtomMemo(node, w)
   304	    return worldMemoRead(node, w)                             // §8
   305	  if node is atom: return k0.value(node)                      // no live tape (invariant F)
   306	  if k0.status(node) is CLEAN_TRACKED: return k0.value(node)  // invariant R
   307	  return worldMemoRead(node, w)                               // stale/pending/fresh/unwatched
   308	```
   309	
   310	### 6.3 Invariant R (routed-serve soundness) — construction unchanged
   311	
   312	As the champion §5.3: `F(n)=0 ∧ CT(n)` at a non-NEWEST read ⇒ the cached
   313	value is world-invariant. The proof leans on (a) CT ⇒ zero recompute, (b)
   314	E-PRESERVE basis-edge completeness, (c) **invariant F's path-transitivity**,
   315	(d) computed purity. Round 1 verified (a), (b), (d); round 2 discovered (c)
   316	was not actually maintained by all sites — §6.4 restores it. R's statement
   317	and proof text are unchanged; its precondition is now true.
   318	
   319	### 6.4 Invariant F, re-proved with maintained path-transitivity (I17)
   320	
   321	**Statement.** For every node p: if a path `x → … → p` exists in the
   322	CURRENT K0∪K1 edge set with `tape(x)` nonempty this episode, then `F(p)=1`.
   323	
   324	**The round-1 hole (TKC-3B, schedule walked at C1-T9).** `afterRetrack`
   325	raised F node-locally. A re-track triggered by something that is not a
   326	receipted-write walk — the two real triggers are a **first evaluation** and
   327	an **fnStamp bump** (`useComputed` closure change: no signal write anywhere)
   328	— can acquire a flagged dep while the node's newest value stays equal;
   329	equality cutoff then leaves downstream nodes CLEAN and unflagged, yet a
   330	real flagged path now runs through them. Invariant R's precondition is
   331	false exactly there, and it serves a divergent value.
   332	
   333	**Repair — one routine, three site classes.** All F mutations go through:
   334	
   335	```
   336	raiseFlag(n):
   337	  if F(n) = 1: return
   338	  F(n) = 1
   339	  for m in K0-out(n) ∪ K1-out(n): raiseFlag(m)     // iterative, scratch stack
   340	```
   341	
   342	- **Site class 1 — receipt walks**: `notifyWalk` (§10) flags every visited
   343	  node; it already traverses the full cone, so it IS a propagation.
   344	- **Site class 2 — edge creation, reader side**: when an evaluation (K0
   345	  re-track/first-track via `afterRetrack`, or a world evaluation recording a
   346	  K1 edge d→n) gives n a dep d with `F(d)=1`, it calls `raiseFlag(n)` — not
   347	  a bare bit-set. E-PRESERVE mirrors need nothing: they copy an edge that
   348	  already existed in K0, so the path set is unchanged.
   349	- **Site class 3 — the flip itself propagates**: `raiseFlag` recurses
   350	  through existing out-edges, stopping at already-flagged nodes.
   351	
   352	**Induction.** Base: episode start — no tapes, all F=0, invariant holds
   353	vacuously. Step over the four event kinds that can create a qualifying path:
   354	(1) first receipt on x: `notifyWalk(x)` flags x's entire current reach
   355	(class 1). (2) new edge u→v with F(u)=1: class 2 raises v; if v flips,
   356	class 3 propagates to v's existing reach — covering every path that the new
   357	edge completed. (3) new edge u→v with F(u)=0: no new flagged path exists
   358	through it; if u later flips, class 3 crosses this edge then. (4) K0
   359	re-track edge REMOVAL: shrinks the path set; a monotone over-approximation
   360	stays valid. No other event mutates edges or tapes. ∎
   361	
   362	**Cost bound.** F is monotone per episode: each node flips at most once, so
   363	`raiseFlag` enqueues ≤ N nodes per episode total; each flipped node scans
   364	its out-edges once; already-flagged stops cost one load per probing edge.
   365	Amortized O(N+E) per episode across ALL raises — the same order as one
   366	notify walk. No hot-path regression class; the per-flip work lands on
   367	re-track/eval paths that are already recompute-priced.
   368	
