   370	
   371	### 7.1 Layout and population (unchanged)
   372	
   373	Per shadow node `{firstOutLink}`; link records `{target, nextOut}`;
   374	bump-allocated; add-only while forked. A cold parallel Int32 column on K0
   375	ids holds `k1IdAndFlag` (bit 0 = F, upper bits = K1 id + episodeEpoch tag)
   376	— cold columns sit outside the interleaving hazard [RESEARCH]. Population:
   377	world evaluations append every dependency actually read (dedup by
   378	link-exists probe); E-PRESERVE mirrors K0 edges before re-track replaces
   379	them (one site, `beforeRetrack`; dev validator priced by SP2).
   380	
   381	### 7.2 Tag lifecycle — the corrected claim (O13)
   382	
   383	The champion §7.4 claimed a tag-wrap collision yields "at worst a shared
   384	record = over-notification." **That claim is withdrawn — three codex
   385	reviews converged on the refutation, and the schedule is a MISS**: a stale
   386	tag that false-matches after wrap points n's column at a K1 id the reset
   387	plane has not re-minted yet; a world evaluation's dedup probe then reads
   388	virgin/garbage space (or, worse, appends an edge into space a later mint
   389	initializes over), so the REAL edge n→m is recorded nowhere current; the
   390	next write's walk through n follows someone else's list and **misses m** —
   391	missed notification, a torn-frame class, not an over-notify class.
   392	
   393	Repair: the tag is 16 bits; when `episodeEpoch mod 2^16` returns to 0 the
   394	quiescence reset **bulk-clears the `k1IdAndFlag` column** (one Int32 fill,
   395	O(N), once per 65,536 episodes) so a stale tag can never false-match.
   396	Forced test: a build with a 2-bit tag drives 5 episodes and asserts (a)
   397	every stale entry re-mints, (b) a seeded pre-wrap edge set still delivers
   398	(differential vs brute-force reach). Row in the §15 table with set/clear
   399	sites (I19 discipline).
