   405	this section repairs the FAMILY: first the enumeration argument (why the
   406	list below is complete), then the unified predicate, then each fingerprint's
   407	construction. The table is the auditable artifact; a CI sweep keeps it
   408	closed as the code grows.
   409	
   410	### 8.1 The enumeration and its closure argument
   411	
   412	A retained world-derived outcome is one of: a world memo `M(node, wKey)`, a
   413	thenable cache entry `(node, lineage, pos)`, an effect dep snapshot, or a
   414	commit-recorded watcher comparison value. Each caches some
   415	`outcome = f_node(inputs)` where, by computed purity (R2/C14: render writes
   416	throw; ambient reads other than signals are the user's declared
   417	non-dependencies), the FREE VARIABLES of the outcome are exactly:
   418	
   419	- the world-folded values of its tracked signal reads,
   420	- the settled state of thenables passed to `ctx.use`,
   421	- the evaluation function itself (`fn`, and for atoms-as-reducers, the
   422	  reducer),
   423	- `ctx.previous` (memo-internal: changes only when the memo's own value
   424	  changes — no external source, §13.3),
   425	- the world identity it was evaluated in,
   426	- the identity of the node records themselves.
   427	
   428	Untracked reads are excluded by contract (§8.5 of the champion, unchanged:
   429	the user opted out of consistency for them, in both planes). Enumerating
   430	the events that can move each free variable gives the closed table:
   431	
   432	| # | change source | what it moves | observer (stamp + conjunct) | clear/reset site | forced test |
   433	|---|---|---|---|---|---|
   434	| S1 | write in slot s | folds for worlds with s∈mask; newest | `slotWriteSeq[s]=seq` at write; conjunct `∀s∈w.mask: wc[s] ≤ r.seq`; atom fingerprint's newest-visible-seq term | wc zeroed at intern and recycle | C1, C5 |
   435	| S2 | retirement of a token (visibility flip, base fold, compaction) | every world's fold; fingerprints of folded atoms | `worldMemoEpoch++` (memos die); `baseSeq = max folded seq` keeps fingerprints monotone through compaction (B1 kill) | epoch monotone per episode; baseSeq persists across episodes, renumber-guarded (§15.3) | C16-B1, C12, C3 |
   436	| S3 | evaluation-function identity (useComputed deps/closure; reducer swap) | `f_node` / reducer | `fnStamp` minted `++globalSeq` at swap; conjunct `r.fnStamp == node.fnStamp`; `reducerStamp` term in the atom fingerprint | die with the node (staging §15.6); dev-warn on reducer swap with pending receipts | C1-T9, C14, O16 differential |
   437	| S4 | thenable settlement (fulfill or reject) | correct outcome of SUSPENSION memos and downstream | eager: settle handler kills sentinel memos via back-refs and re-delivers; belt conjunct: `r.kind = SUSPENSION ⇒ r.thenable still pending`; generation-checked late settles no-op | entries/memos die with lineage (commit/abandon) | C15 steps 2–4 + settle-race property test |
   438	| S5 | episode boundary / counter renumber | the number line under every stamp | `episodeEpoch` in worldKey; epoch tag on the K1 column (wrap-clear §7.2); renumber rewrites the retained stamp columns (§15.3); every cross-episode retainer epoch-guarded (I8) | quiescence reset | C13 battery, forced-small builds |
   439	| S6 | world identity (mask, pin, per-root lockedIn) | which fold is being asked for | structural: in the KEY (worldKey interns), never a conjunct | worldKey interns die at retirement/quiescence; lockedIn bits cleared at retirement (§5.3.5) | C11 |
   440	| S7 | node-identity recycle (staged reclaim, free lists) | what `(node, …)` keys denote | GEN-tagged ids (donor free-list discipline); reclamation deferred to quiescence so mid-episode references never dangle (§15.6) | GEN bump at free-list reinsertion | S15 high-water test |
   441	
   442	**Closure argument.** The free-variable list is complete by purity (the
   443	evaluator can observe nothing else; `__DEV__` builds assert it by running
   444	evals under a frame that intercepts engine reads). Each free variable's
   445	every mutation path is one of S1–S7: signal values change only by write
   446	(S1) or fold/visibility change (S2) or reducer/function change (S3) on the
   447	one number line whose integrity is S5; thenables change only by settlement
   448	(S4); world identity is the key (S6); record identity is S7. **Audit rule
   449	(CI)**: the world-eval frame's input surface is declared in the schema
